## 7. HID Capture on PC 1 (Non‐Exclusive Raw Input)

### 7.1 Windows (Raw Input)

1. **Register for Raw Input**

   ```c
   RAWINPUTDEVICE rid;
   rid.usUsagePage = 0x01;         // Generic desktop controls
   rid.usUsage = 0x02;             // Mouse
   rid.dwFlags = RIDEV_INPUTSINK;  // Receive events even when in background
   rid.hwndTarget = hWnd;          // Your application window handle
   RegisterRawInputDevices(&rid, 1, sizeof(rid));
   ```
2. **Process WM\_INPUT**

   ```c
   UINT dwSize;
   GetRawInputData((HRAWINPUT)lParam, RID_INPUT, NULL, &dwSize, sizeof(RAWINPUTHEADER));
   LPBYTE lpb = malloc(dwSize);
   GetRawInputData((HRAWINPUT)lParam, RID_INPUT, lpb, &dwSize, sizeof(RAWINPUTHEADER));
   RAWINPUT* raw = (RAWINPUT*)lpb;
   if (raw->header.dwType == RIM_TYPEMOUSE) {
     // raw->data.mouse.lLastX, lLastY for dx, dy
     // raw->data.mouse.usButtonFlags for button presses/releases
     // raw->data.mouse.usButtonFlags == RI_MOUSE_WHEEL for scroll
   }
   free(lpb);
   ```
3. **Ensure Non‐Exclusive**

   * Do NOT set `RIDEV_CAPTUREMOUSE` or `RIDEV_NOLEGACY`. With only `RIDEV_INPUTSINK`, the OS still moves the native cursor.

### 7.2 Linux (evdev)

1. **Identify Mouse Device**

   ```bash
   ls /dev/input/by-id/    # find your BT mouse (name contains “mouse” or vendor ID)
   ```
2. **Open in Non‐Exclusive Mode**

   ```c
   int fd = open("/dev/input/eventX", O_RDONLY | O_NONBLOCK);
   // Do NOT ioctl(fd, EVIOCGRAB, 1). That would be exclusive.
   ```
3. **Read Events**

   ```c
   struct input_event ev;
   while (read(fd, &ev, sizeof(ev)) > 0) {
     if (ev.type == EV_REL) {
       if (ev.code == REL_X) dx = ev.value;
       if (ev.code == REL_Y) dy = ev.value;
       if (ev.code == REL_WHEEL) scrollDelta = ev.value;
     }
     if (ev.type == EV_KEY) {
       // Button press/release: ev.code = BTN_LEFT, BTN_RIGHT, BTN_MIDDLE, etc.
       // ev.value = 1 (down), 0 (up), 2 (auto‐repeat)
     }
   }
   ```
4. **Let X/Wayland See It**

   * Because you didn’t `EVIOCGRAB`, the kernel still dispatches the same events to your window manager. Cursor moves normally.

### 7.3 macOS (IOHIDManager)

1. **Set Up IOHIDManager**

   ```objc
   IOHIDManagerRef hidManager = IOHIDManagerCreate(kCFAllocatorDefault, kIOHIDOptionsTypeNone);
   NSDictionary *matchingDict = @{
     @(kIOHIDDeviceUsagePage): @(kHIDPage_GenericDesktop),
     @(kIOHIDDeviceUsage): @(kHIDUsage_GD_Mouse)
   };
   IOHIDManagerSetDeviceMatching(hidManager, (__bridge CFDictionaryRef)matchingDict);
   IOHIDManagerRegisterInputValueCallback(hidManager, Handle_Input, NULL);
   IOHIDManagerScheduleWithRunLoop(hidManager, CFRunLoopGetCurrent(), kCFRunLoopDefaultMode);
   IOHIDManagerOpen(hidManager, kIOHIDOptionsTypeNone);
   ```
2. **Callback Implementation**

   ```objc
   void Handle_Input(void *context, IOReturn result, void *sender, IOHIDValueRef value) {
     IOHIDElementRef element = IOHIDValueGetElement(value);
     uint32_t usagePage = IOHIDElementGetUsagePage(element);
     uint32_t usage = IOHIDElementGetUsage(element);
     int32_t intValue = IOHIDValueGetIntegerValue(value);
     if (usagePage == kHIDPage_GenericDesktop && usage == kHIDUsage_GD_X) {
       dx = intValue;
     }
     if (usagePage == kHIDPage_GenericDesktop && usage == kHIDUsage_GD_Y) {
       dy = intValue;
     }
     if (usagePage == kHIDPage_Button) {
       // intValue = 1 (down) or 0 (up) for button events
     }
     if (usagePage == kHIDPage_GenericDesktop && usage == kHIDUsage_GD_Wheel) {
       scrollDelta = intValue;
     }
     // Package these into an INPUT_EVENT and send if forwarding is ON
   }
   ```
3. **Non‐Exclusive:**

   * Do **not** set `kIOHIDOptionsTypeSeizeDevice`. By default, with only `kIOHIDOptionsTypeNone`, you receive events alongside the OS cursor.

